?  I personally favor QxPa3.  Sure, it leaves Pc6 undefended, but QxPc6 would be answered by Qd6+ followed by a queen exchange.  White's pawns are all blocked and defended only by white's black bishop.  Meanwhile, black could focus on promoting the a pawn or toppling the white king.

Now Ph6 is vulnerable.  Pc5 lets the black queen defend Ph6, but Pc7 would be vulnerable.  QxPc7, Qg6.  Qd8+ Kh7.  Qg6 would then be followed by a queen exchange--or white#.  or white might move Qf3 to protect Pg2.  Black is so far ahead sacrificing a queen and bishop for white's queen and pawn still results in a black victory.
?  I don't see black's strategy.  personally I'm partial to qf5.  PxPg6, Qh5+.  White either trades queens or loses the bishop.  If white answers with QxPc7, QxPh5+ wins white's bishop for free.
